+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RdDYoftjEtHEufF9p3Hp5k","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→import express from 'express';\n     2→import { createStore } from './store.js';\n     3→import { authMiddleware } from './middleware.js';\n     4→import { authRoutes } from './routes/auth.js';\n     5→import { folderRoutes } from './routes/folders.js';\n     6→import { documentRoutes } from './routes/documents.js';\n     7→import { activityRoutes } from './routes/activity.js';\n     8→\n     9→export function createApp() {\n    10→  const app = express();\n    11→  const store = createStore();\n    12→\n    13→  app.use(express.json());\n    14→  app.use(authMiddleware(store));\n    15→\n    16→  app.use('/auth', authRoutes(store));\n    17→  app.use('/folders', folderRoutes(store));\n    18→  app.use('/documents', documentRoutes(store));\n    19→  app.use('/activity', activityRoutes(store));\n    20→\n    21→  return app;\n    22→}\n    23→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0158hvw9xtXLqpKc4qGFnLSF","session_id":"9cfe4609-ae8b-4666-82c5-b0be39bd6a82","uuid":"18e31b68-5b06-413c-87cb-934c47be97e7"}
+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0158hvw9xtXLqpKc4qGFnLSF","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture of the implementation. Here is my thorough review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Document Management API\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY -- Security Issues\n\n#### S1. Passwords stored in plain text (`/workspace/src/routes/auth.ts`, line 26; `/workspace/src/types.ts`, line 5)\n\nPasswords are stored directly on the `User` object without any hashing. The registration endpoint stores the raw password:\n\n```typescript\nconst user = { id, username, password };  // line 26\nstore.users.set(id, user);\n```\n\nAnd login compares against the raw password:\n\n```typescript\nif (user.username === username && user.password === password) {  // line 42\n```\n\nPasswords must be hashed with bcrypt (or similar) before storage and compared using a constant-time comparison function.\n\n#### S2. Tokens stored in plain text and only one token per user (`/workspace/src/routes/auth.ts`, line 43; `/workspace/src/middleware.ts`, line 15)\n\nThe authentication token is stored directly on the `User` object. Each new login overwrites the previous token (line 44: `user.token = token`), meaning logging in on a second device invalidates the first session without notice. Tokens should be hashed before storage and looked up via a token-to-user mapping rather than iterating all users on every request.\n\n#### S3. Token lookup is O(n) over all users (`/workspace/src/middleware.ts`, lines 14-18)\n\n```typescript\nfor (const user of store.users.values()) {\n  if (user.token === token) {\n```\n\nEvery authenticated request iterates over every user in the store. This is both a performance issue and a timing side-channel: the time to authenticate varies depending on where in the map the user falls. Use a `Map<token, userId>` for O(1) lookup.\n\n#### S4. Password is leaked in responses (`/workspace/src/routes/auth.ts`, line 29; `/workspace/src/types.ts`)\n\nWhen the register endpoint returns the user, it manually constructs `{ id, username }`, which is fine. However, the `User` object including the `password` field is attached to `req.user` by the auth middleware (line 16 of middleware.ts) and is the same object stored in the map. Any accidental serialization of `req.user` anywhere else in the codebase would leak the password. The `User` type should separate credentials from the profile, or the password should be stripped before attaching to the request.\n\n#### S5. Activity log exposes all data to any authenticated user (`/workspace/src/routes/activity.ts`, lines 9-11)\n\n```typescript\nrouter.get('/', requireAuth, (_req: AuthenticatedRequest, res) => {\n  res.json(store.activityLog);\n});\n```\n\nAny authenticated user can see the entire activity log, including activity on documents and folders they have no access to. This is a significant information disclosure vulnerability. The activity log should be filtered to show only entries for resources the requesting user has at least read access to.\n\n#### S6. Editors can escalate to owner-level sharing via share update (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 222-240; `/workspace/src/routes/documents.ts`, lines 198-215)\n\nWhen updating an existing share, the code does **not** re-check whether the sharing user is allowed to grant the new role. The guard on line 211 (folders) / line 186 (documents) that prevents non-owners from granting owner role only runs on the initial check. But the existing-share update path at line 228 (folders) / line 202 (documents) bypasses it -- an editor who previously created a viewer share can later update it to `owner` because the `shareRole === 'owner' && role !== 'owner'` guard has already been passed:\n\n```typescript\n// The guard is at line 211 for folders:\nif (shareRole === 'owner' && role !== 'owner') {\n  res.status(403).json({ error: 'Only owners can grant owner role' });\n  return;\n}\n\n// But the existing-share update at line 228 runs AFTER this guard:\nif (existingShare) {\n  existingShare.role = shareRole;  // Updates without re-checking!\n```\n\nWait -- re-reading more carefully, the guard at line 211 actually runs *before* the existing-share check at line 223. So the sequence is: validate `shareRole` -> reject if `shareRole === 'owner'` and user is not owner -> then check existing share. This means the guard does protect the update path as well. **This is actually correct upon closer inspection.** I retract this finding.\n\n#### S7. Users can share resources with themselves (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, `/workspace/src/routes/documents.ts`)\n\nThere is no check preventing a user from sharing a resource with themselves. An editor could share a document with themselves as `editor` (or higher, subject to the owner-role guard), creating duplicate share entries. While not a direct escalation (because the \"most permissive role wins\" logic handles duplicates), it creates unnecessary clutter and could be used to circumvent future share-revocation logic.\n\n---\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY -- Logic Bugs\n\n#### L1. Incomplete circular reference check in folder update (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 103-117)\n\nThe update route only prevents a folder from being set as its own parent:\n\n```typescript\nif (parentId === folder.id) {\n  res.status(400).json({ error: 'Folder cannot be its own parent' });\n  return;\n}\n```\n\nThis does **not** prevent deeper cycles. For example, if folder A contains folder B, and you move folder A to be a child of folder B, you create a cycle (A -> B -> A). The `getEffectiveRole` function recurses up the `parentId` chain and would enter an **infinite loop** on such a cycle, crashing the server with a stack overflow. The code must walk up the proposed parent chain and verify the folder being moved is not an ancestor of the new parent.\n\n#### L2. Recursive folder deletion while iterating over the Map (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 138-168)\n\nThe `deleteChildren` function iterates over `store.folders.entries()` while simultaneously calling `store.folders.delete(childId)` inside the loop, and the outer delete loop for documents does the same with `store.documents.entries()`. Deleting entries from a `Map` during `for...of` iteration is actually defined behavior in JavaScript (the deleted entry won't be revisited, and entries added after current position will be visited). However, the nested structure -- iterating folders to find children, then deleting documents from a separate map inside that loop -- combined with the recursive call, means the recursion happens **before** the current child is deleted (line 162-163). This works in practice but is fragile and hard to reason about. A safer approach is to collect all descendant IDs first, then delete in a second pass.\n\n#### L3. Folder deletion does not log activity (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 122-180)\n\nThe folder delete endpoint does not push any entries to the activity log -- neither for the folder being deleted nor for the documents being deleted as part of the cascade. According to the requirements, delete events should be tracked. Compare with `documents.ts` which does log `document_deleted`.\n\n#### L4. Folder creation does not log activity (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 10-45)\n\nNo activity log entry is created when a folder is created. The requirements state \"Activity log tracking document create/update/delete and sharing events.\" While this could be read as only applying to documents, folder sharing *is* logged, suggesting folder lifecycle events should also be tracked. At minimum, this is inconsistent.\n\n#### L5. Folder update does not log activity (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 82-120)\n\nSame issue: no activity log entry when a folder is renamed or moved.\n\n#### L6. `canShare` function is imported but never used (`/workspace/src/permissions.ts`, line 79-81; `/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, line 4; `/workspace/src/routes/documents.ts`, line 4)\n\nThe `canShare` function exists in `permissions.ts` and is correctly defined:\n\n```typescript\nexport function canShare(role: Role | null): boolean {\n  return role === 'editor' || role === 'owner';\n}\n```\n\nBut it is **never imported or used** in the route files. Instead, the sharing endpoints use inline, redundant logic:\n\n```typescript\n// folders.ts line 193:\nif (!canEdit(role) && role !== 'owner') {\n\n// documents.ts line 168:\nif (!canEdit(role) && role !== 'owner') {\n```\n\nThe expression `!canEdit(role) && role !== 'owner'` is equivalent to `!canEdit(role)` because `canEdit` already returns `true` for `'owner'`. This means the `&& role !== 'owner'` is dead code. The logic is *functionally correct* (editors and owners can share), but it should use `canShare(role)` for clarity and maintainability.\n\n#### L7. No permission check when moving a folder to a new parent (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 103-117)\n\nWhen updating a folder's `parentId`, the code verifies the new parent exists but does **not** verify that the user has write permissions on the new parent folder. A user could move a folder they own into another user's folder that they only have viewer access to (or no access to at all). The same `canEdit` check applied during folder creation should be applied to the destination parent during a move.\n\n---\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY -- Missing Features from Requirements\n\n#### M1. No way to list folders at root level\n\nThere is no `GET /folders` endpoint to list all top-level folders (or folders accessible to the user). Users can only retrieve a folder by its specific ID. If a user doesn't know the folder IDs, they have no way to discover them.\n\n#### M2. No way to list documents\n\nSimilarly, there is no `GET /documents` endpoint to list all documents accessible to the user.\n\n#### M3. No unshare / revoke access endpoint\n\nThere is no way to remove a share once granted. The requirements mention sharing with roles, but there is no way to revoke access. At minimum, owners should be able to remove shares.\n\n#### M4. No way to list shares on a resource\n\nThere is no endpoint to view who has access to a folder or document and with what role.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM PRIORITY -- Code Quality Issues\n\n#### Q1. Redundant permission check expression in share routes\n\nAs noted in L6, the share permission checks use:\n\n```typescript\nif (!canEdit(role) && role !== 'owner')\n```\n\nSince `canEdit` already returns `true` for owners, `role !== 'owner'` is always `true` when `!canEdit(role)` is `true`. The condition simplifies to `!canEdit(role)` or, better, `!canShare(role)`.\n\n#### Q2. Inconsistent ID generation (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 230-231, 244; `/workspace/src/routes/documents.ts`, lines 205, 218-219)\n\nShare objects and activity log entries use `String(store.nextId++)` directly instead of the `generateId(store)` helper function. This is inconsistent and risks ID collisions if `generateId` is ever changed to use a different scheme. All ID generation should go through the same function.\n\n#### Q3. `generateId` is not concurrency-safe (`/workspace/src/store.ts`, lines 23-25)\n\nWhile this is an in-memory single-threaded Node.js application, the `nextId++` pattern is fragile. If the app were ever adapted for concurrent use, this would break. The direct `store.nextId++` calls in route files (see Q2) make this worse.\n\n#### Q4. No input sanitization or length validation\n\nThere is no validation on the length or content of `username`, `password`, `name`, `title`, or `content` fields. A user could create a document with a multi-gigabyte content string, exhausting server memory. Basic length limits should be enforced.\n\n#### Q5. No pagination on activity log (`/workspace/src/routes/activity.ts`)\n\nThe activity log returns the entire array with no pagination. Over time this will grow without bound and responses will become very large.\n\n#### Q6. Mutable objects returned directly from the store\n\nRoute handlers return folder and document objects directly from the store maps (e.g., `res.json(folder)` at `folders.ts` line 119 after mutation). While this works, it means the same mutable object is both in the store and was just sent as a response. Any accidental mutation between response serialization and subsequent requests could cause subtle bugs. Returning copies would be safer.\n\n#### Q7. `parentId` accepts falsy values as \"no parent\" (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, line 116)\n\n```typescript\nfolder.parentId = parentId || null;\n```\n\nThe `||` operator treats `\"\"`, `0`, and `false` as falsy, converting them all to `null`. This is probably fine since `parentId` should be a string ID, but using `?? null` (nullish coalescing) would be more precise and intentional.\n\n#### Q8. No `express.json()` body size limit (`/workspace/src/app.ts`, line 13)\n\n```typescript\napp.use(express.json());\n```\n\nThere is no body size limit configured. Express's default is 100kb, which is reasonable, but this should be explicitly set for clarity and to prevent accidental changes in Express defaults from affecting the app.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Critical Findings\n\n| # | Severity | Category | Description |\n|---|----------|----------|-------------|\n| S1 | HIGH | Security | Plain-text password storage |\n| S5 | HIGH | Security | Activity log leaks all data to any user |\n| L1 | HIGH | Logic Bug | Incomplete cycle detection causes infinite recursion |\n| L6 | HIGH | Logic Bug | `canShare` defined but never used; inline logic is confusing |\n| L7 | HIGH | Logic Bug | No permission check on destination when moving folders |\n| L3 | HIGH | Logic Bug | Folder deletion not logged in activity |\n| Q2 | MEDIUM | Quality | Inconsistent ID generation bypasses `generateId` |\n\nThe most severe issue is **L1** (circular reference in folder hierarchy causing infinite recursion / stack overflow crash). An attacker with editor access to two folders can crash the server at will. The second most severe is **S5** (full activity log disclosure to any authenticated user), which leaks information about all users' actions across all resources."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a19aa6a (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 25003\ntool_uses: 9\nduration_ms: 86881</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9cfe4609-ae8b-4666-82c5-b0be39bd6a82","uuid":"3cdd8529-d5c8-492b-a615-703e47cdcdf9","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are a code reviewer. Review the following implementation of a document management API. Focus on:\n1. Security issues (HIGH priority)\n2. Logic bugs (HIGH priority)\n3. Missing features from requirements (HIGH priority)\n4. Code quality issues (MEDIUM priority)\n\nThe implementation consists of these files:\n\n**src/types.ts** - Data models\n**src/store.ts** - In-memory storage\n**src/middleware.ts** - Auth middleware\n**src/permissions.ts** - Permission checking\n**src/routes/auth.ts** - Auth routes (register/login)\n**src/routes/folders.ts** - Folder CRUD + sharing\n**src/routes/documents.ts** - Document CRUD + sharing\n**src/routes/activity.ts** - Activity log\n**src/app.ts** - Main app factory\n\nPlease read all these files and provide your review. The requirements are:\n- User management (register, login with token-based auth)\n- Hierarchical folders (nested, CRUD)\n- Documents (CRUD, belong to folders)\n- Sharing with 3 roles: viewer (read), editor (read+modify+share), owner (full control)\n- Creator is auto-owner\n- Most permissive role wins when multiple access paths exist\n- Activity log tracking document create/update/delete and sharing events\n- RESTful API with proper status codes\n- createApp() exported from app.ts\n\nLook specifically for:\n- Permission bypass vulnerabilities\n- Missing validation\n- Incorrect permission inheritance logic\n- Edge cases in recursive folder operations\n- Whether the sharing check (`canShare`) correctly allows editors AND owners to share","agentId":"a19aa6a","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture of the implementation. Here is my thorough review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Document Management API\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY -- Security Issues\n\n#### S1. Passwords stored in plain text (`/workspace/src/routes/auth.ts`, line 26; `/workspace/src/types.ts`, line 5)\n\nPasswords are stored directly on the `User` object without any hashing. The registration endpoint stores the raw password:\n\n```typescript\nconst user = { id, username, password };  // line 26\nstore.users.set(id, user);\n```\n\nAnd login compares against the raw password:\n\n```typescript\nif (user.username === username && user.password === password) {  // line 42\n```\n\nPasswords must be hashed with bcrypt (or similar) before storage and compared using a constant-time comparison function.\n\n#### S2. Tokens stored in plain text and only one token per user (`/workspace/src/routes/auth.ts`, line 43; `/workspace/src/middleware.ts`, line 15)\n\nThe authentication token is stored directly on the `User` object. Each new login overwrites the previous token (line 44: `user.token = token`), meaning logging in on a second device invalidates the first session without notice. Tokens should be hashed before storage and looked up via a token-to-user mapping rather than iterating all users on every request.\n\n#### S3. Token lookup is O(n) over all users (`/workspace/src/middleware.ts`, lines 14-18)\n\n```typescript\nfor (const user of store.users.values()) {\n  if (user.token === token) {\n```\n\nEvery authenticated request iterates over every user in the store. This is both a performance issue and a timing side-channel: the time to authenticate varies depending on where in the map the user falls. Use a `Map<token, userId>` for O(1) lookup.\n\n#### S4. Password is leaked in responses (`/workspace/src/routes/auth.ts`, line 29; `/workspace/src/types.ts`)\n\nWhen the register endpoint returns the user, it manually constructs `{ id, username }`, which is fine. However, the `User` object including the `password` field is attached to `req.user` by the auth middleware (line 16 of middleware.ts) and is the same object stored in the map. Any accidental serialization of `req.user` anywhere else in the codebase would leak the password. The `User` type should separate credentials from the profile, or the password should be stripped before attaching to the request.\n\n#### S5. Activity log exposes all data to any authenticated user (`/workspace/src/routes/activity.ts`, lines 9-11)\n\n```typescript\nrouter.get('/', requireAuth, (_req: AuthenticatedRequest, res) => {\n  res.json(store.activityLog);\n});\n```\n\nAny authenticated user can see the entire activity log, including activity on documents and folders they have no access to. This is a significant information disclosure vulnerability. The activity log should be filtered to show only entries for resources the requesting user has at least read access to.\n\n#### S6. Editors can escalate to owner-level sharing via share update (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 222-240; `/workspace/src/routes/documents.ts`, lines 198-215)\n\nWhen updating an existing share, the code does **not** re-check whether the sharing user is allowed to grant the new role. The guard on line 211 (folders) / line 186 (documents) that prevents non-owners from granting owner role only runs on the initial check. But the existing-share update path at line 228 (folders) / line 202 (documents) bypasses it -- an editor who previously created a viewer share can later update it to `owner` because the `shareRole === 'owner' && role !== 'owner'` guard has already been passed:\n\n```typescript\n// The guard is at line 211 for folders:\nif (shareRole === 'owner' && role !== 'owner') {\n  res.status(403).json({ error: 'Only owners can grant owner role' });\n  return;\n}\n\n// But the existing-share update at line 228 runs AFTER this guard:\nif (existingShare) {\n  existingShare.role = shareRole;  // Updates without re-checking!\n```\n\nWait -- re-reading more carefully, the guard at line 211 actually runs *before* the existing-share check at line 223. So the sequence is: validate `shareRole` -> reject if `shareRole === 'owner'` and user is not owner -> then check existing share. This means the guard does protect the update path as well. **This is actually correct upon closer inspection.** I retract this finding.\n\n#### S7. Users can share resources with themselves (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, `/workspace/src/routes/documents.ts`)\n\nThere is no check preventing a user from sharing a resource with themselves. An editor could share a document with themselves as `editor` (or higher, subject to the owner-role guard), creating duplicate share entries. While not a direct escalation (because the \"most permissive role wins\" logic handles duplicates), it creates unnecessary clutter and could be used to circumvent future share-revocation logic.\n\n---\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY -- Logic Bugs\n\n#### L1. Incomplete circular reference check in folder update (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 103-117)\n\nThe update route only prevents a folder from being set as its own parent:\n\n```typescript\nif (parentId === folder.id) {\n  res.status(400).json({ error: 'Folder cannot be its own parent' });\n  return;\n}\n```\n\nThis does **not** prevent deeper cycles. For example, if folder A contains folder B, and you move folder A to be a child of folder B, you create a cycle (A -> B -> A). The `getEffectiveRole` function recurses up the `parentId` chain and would enter an **infinite loop** on such a cycle, crashing the server with a stack overflow. The code must walk up the proposed parent chain and verify the folder being moved is not an ancestor of the new parent.\n\n#### L2. Recursive folder deletion while iterating over the Map (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 138-168)\n\nThe `deleteChildren` function iterates over `store.folders.entries()` while simultaneously calling `store.folders.delete(childId)` inside the loop, and the outer delete loop for documents does the same with `store.documents.entries()`. Deleting entries from a `Map` during `for...of` iteration is actually defined behavior in JavaScript (the deleted entry won't be revisited, and entries added after current position will be visited). However, the nested structure -- iterating folders to find children, then deleting documents from a separate map inside that loop -- combined with the recursive call, means the recursion happens **before** the current child is deleted (line 162-163). This works in practice but is fragile and hard to reason about. A safer approach is to collect all descendant IDs first, then delete in a second pass.\n\n#### L3. Folder deletion does not log activity (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 122-180)\n\nThe folder delete endpoint does not push any entries to the activity log -- neither for the folder being deleted nor for the documents being deleted as part of the cascade. According to the requirements, delete events should be tracked. Compare with `documents.ts` which does log `document_deleted`.\n\n#### L4. Folder creation does not log activity (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 10-45)\n\nNo activity log entry is created when a folder is created. The requirements state \"Activity log tracking document create/update/delete and sharing events.\" While this could be read as only applying to documents, folder sharing *is* logged, suggesting folder lifecycle events should also be tracked. At minimum, this is inconsistent.\n\n#### L5. Folder update does not log activity (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 82-120)\n\nSame issue: no activity log entry when a folder is renamed or moved.\n\n#### L6. `canShare` function is imported but never used (`/workspace/src/permissions.ts`, line 79-81; `/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, line 4; `/workspace/src/routes/documents.ts`, line 4)\n\nThe `canShare` function exists in `permissions.ts` and is correctly defined:\n\n```typescript\nexport function canShare(role: Role | null): boolean {\n  return role === 'editor' || role === 'owner';\n}\n```\n\nBut it is **never imported or used** in the route files. Instead, the sharing endpoints use inline, redundant logic:\n\n```typescript\n// folders.ts line 193:\nif (!canEdit(role) && role !== 'owner') {\n\n// documents.ts line 168:\nif (!canEdit(role) && role !== 'owner') {\n```\n\nThe expression `!canEdit(role) && role !== 'owner'` is equivalent to `!canEdit(role)` because `canEdit` already returns `true` for `'owner'`. This means the `&& role !== 'owner'` is dead code. The logic is *functionally correct* (editors and owners can share), but it should use `canShare(role)` for clarity and maintainability.\n\n#### L7. No permission check when moving a folder to a new parent (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 103-117)\n\nWhen updating a folder's `parentId`, the code verifies the new parent exists but does **not** verify that the user has write permissions on the new parent folder. A user could move a folder they own into another user's folder that they only have viewer access to (or no access to at all). The same `canEdit` check applied during folder creation should be applied to the destination parent during a move.\n\n---\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY -- Missing Features from Requirements\n\n#### M1. No way to list folders at root level\n\nThere is no `GET /folders` endpoint to list all top-level folders (or folders accessible to the user). Users can only retrieve a folder by its specific ID. If a user doesn't know the folder IDs, they have no way to discover them.\n\n#### M2. No way to list documents\n\nSimilarly, there is no `GET /documents` endpoint to list all documents accessible to the user.\n\n#### M3. No unshare / revoke access endpoint\n\nThere is no way to remove a share once granted. The requirements mention sharing with roles, but there is no way to revoke access. At minimum, owners should be able to remove shares.\n\n#### M4. No way to list shares on a resource\n\nThere is no endpoint to view who has access to a folder or document and with what role.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM PRIORITY -- Code Quality Issues\n\n#### Q1. Redundant permission check expression in share routes\n\nAs noted in L6, the share permission checks use:\n\n```typescript\nif (!canEdit(role) && role !== 'owner')\n```\n\nSince `canEdit` already returns `true` for owners, `role !== 'owner'` is always `true` when `!canEdit(role)` is `true`. The condition simplifies to `!canEdit(role)` or, better, `!canShare(role)`.\n\n#### Q2. Inconsistent ID generation (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 230-231, 244; `/workspace/src/routes/documents.ts`, lines 205, 218-219)\n\nShare objects and activity log entries use `String(store.nextId++)` directly instead of the `generateId(store)` helper function. This is inconsistent and risks ID collisions if `generateId` is ever changed to use a different scheme. All ID generation should go through the same function.\n\n#### Q3. `generateId` is not concurrency-safe (`/workspace/src/store.ts`, lines 23-25)\n\nWhile this is an in-memory single-threaded Node.js application, the `nextId++` pattern is fragile. If the app were ever adapted for concurrent use, this would break. The direct `store.nextId++` calls in route files (see Q2) make this worse.\n\n#### Q4. No input sanitization or length validation\n\nThere is no validation on the length or content of `username`, `password`, `name`, `title`, or `content` fields. A user could create a document with a multi-gigabyte content string, exhausting server memory. Basic length limits should be enforced.\n\n#### Q5. No pagination on activity log (`/workspace/src/routes/activity.ts`)\n\nThe activity log returns the entire array with no pagination. Over time this will grow without bound and responses will